                <div class="post content">
    <h2><a href="/2009/10/cyclomatic-complexity-in-vim-first-steps.html">Cyclomatic Complexity in Vim: First Steps</a></h2>
    <div class="date">25 Oct 2009</div>
    <p>I've been kicking around the idea of integrating complexity analysis with vim.  Tonight, I spent a couple hours getting a proof of concept working (for Python code, naturally). Each line gets highlighted based on the complexity of the function: green for low, yellow for medium, red for high.</p>

<p><img src="/images/vim_complexity.png" alt="screenshot of vim complexity plugin" /></p>

<p>A static image doesn't really do it justice &ndash; the highlighting updates whenever you write a file. There's a <a href="http://vimeo.com/7259161">15 second video</a> of me demoing it that's much better than the picture above.</p>

<p>This is based on <a href="http://www.traceback.org">Dave Stanek</a>'s <a href="http://www.traceback.org/2008/03/31/measuring-cyclomatic-complexity-of-python-code">cyclomatic complexity code</a>. It's hacked together and the complexity algorithm seems slightly wrong (unless I'm remembering it incorrectly). However, it does successfully compute the complexity and highlight the code, which is good enough for a blog post. ;)</p>

<p>If you're feeling adventurous, you can find the source code <a href="http://bitbucket.org/garybernhardt/pycomplexity">on BitBucket</a>.</p>

</div>


